    "constituents_description": "The most important healing constituents of Calendula officinalis are flavonoids like kaempferol and quercetin, which exhibit anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties; saponins, which have antimicrobial and anti-inflammatory effects; carotenoids such as caroten and violaxanthin, which act as antioxidants to protect against cell damage; triterpene esters, specifically calendula esters like calendulin and calendrin, which possess antimicrobial and anti-inflammatory properties; and triterpenoids, which have been shown to exhibit anti-inflammatory and immunomodulatory effects. These constituents work synergistically to provide Calendula officinalis with its therapeutic potential. The anti-inflammatory effects of these constituents may contribute to the herb's ability to promote wound healing and tissue repair. Flavonoids and triterpenoids in Calendula officinalis have been shown to inhibit the production of pro-inflammatory cytokines. The antioxidant properties of carotenoids and flavonoids in Calendula officinalis may help protect against oxidative stress and cell damage.",
